"Svenning J.-C., Skov F.","Potential impact of climate change on the northern nemoral forest herb flora of Europe",2006,"Biodiversity and Conservation","15","10",,"3341","3356",,,10.1007/s10531-005-1345-8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33750814848&partnerID=40&md5=605caa4707f5be8ecd143ea138c29bee","Department of Biological Sciences, University of Aarhus, Ny Munkegade, Bygn. 540, Univ., DK-8000 Aarhus C, Denmark; Department of Wildlife Ecology and Biodiversity, National Environmental Research Institute of Denmark, Kalø, Grenaavej 12, DK-8410, Rønde, Denmark","Svenning, J.-C., Department of Biological Sciences, University of Aarhus, Ny Munkegade, Bygn. 540, Univ., DK-8000 Aarhus C, Denmark; Skov, F., Department of Wildlife Ecology and Biodiversity, National Environmental Research Institute of Denmark, Kalø, Grenaavej 12, DK-8410, Rønde, Denmark","This study examines the potential impact on 21st century climate change on north- nemoral forest herb ranges at three spatial scales (Europe as whole, Northern/Southern Europe, separately, and the small north-nemoral region Denmark) and for two contrasting geographic regions (Northern and Southern Europe), and evaluates which species traits (climatic niche parameters, range location) would be most important for the range responses. The impact of climate change on the ranges of 36 north-nemoral forest herb species was estimated using a fuzzy bioclimatic envelope model that link atlas data to climate to predict bioclimatic suitability. Two global warming scenarios were investigated. Bioclimatic suitability was predicted to decline for all species in Europe as whole and in Southern Europe, while a minority would experience stable or increased suitability in Denmark and Northern Europe. No species were predicted to go extinct at a European scale under any scenario, although up to 14% of the species could be lost at the smallest scale. However, due to its strong impact on Southern Europe, warming would threaten the long-term survival of the nemoral flora. In particular in Northern Europe suitability increases would occur in unoccupied areas. Hence, dispersal limitation could be a particularly important constraint on species responses to climate change in this region. The best predictors of modelled large-scale sensitivity to global warming often included water balance niche descriptors and the latitudinal range centroid. © 2006 Springer.","Bioclimatic envelope modelling; Dispersal limitation; Drought; Geographic variability; Global warming; Range shifts; Spatial scale","climate change; dispersal; flora; geographical region; herb; survival; Denmark; Eurasia; Europe; Northern Europe; Scandinavia; Southern Europe",,,,,,"Bakkenes, M., Alkemade, J.R.M., Ihle, F., Leemans, R., Latour, J.B., Assessing effects of forecasted climate change on the diversity and distribution of European higher plants for 2050 (2002) Glob. Change Biol., 8, pp. 390-407; Bennett, K.D., Tzedakis, P.C., Willis, K.J., Quaternary refugia of north European trees (1991) J. Biogeogr., 18, pp. 103-115; Berger, T.D., Loutre, M.F., An exceptionally long interglacial ahead? (2002) Science, 297, pp. 1287-1288; Box, E.O., Crumpacker, D.W., Hardin, E.D., Predicted effects of climatic change on distribution of ecologically important native tree and shrub species in Florida (1999) Climatic Change, 41, pp. 213-248; Breckle, S.-W., (2002) Walter's Vegetation of the Earth, , Springer-Verlag, Berlin, Germany; Brunet, J., Von Oheimb, G., Migration of vascular plants to secondary woodlands in southern Sweden (1998) J. Ecol., 86, pp. 429-438; Ellenberg, H., (1988) Vegetation Ecology of Central Europe, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK; Fosaa, A.M., Sykes, M.T., Lawesson, J.E., Gaard, M., Potential effects of climate change on plant species in the Faroe Islands (2004) Glob. Ecol. Biogeogr., 13, pp. 427-437; Graae, B.J., Økland, R.H., Petersen, P.M., Jensen, K., Fritzbøger, B., Influence of historical, geographical 